// ■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■■
// Oscillators {

// @function  RSI (Relative Strengh Index). Measures the relative strength of recent price gains to recent price losses of an asset.
// @param source    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length    (int) Period of loopback
// @returns         (float) Series of RSI
export rsi(float source, simple int length) =>
    ta.rsi(source, length)

// @function    Asymmetrical RSI. Measures the relative strength of recent price gains to recent price losses of an asset.
// It uses an asymmetrical approach to calculate the RSI. It uses two different alpha values for the up and down movements.
// The asymmetrical RSI is more responsive to price changes than the traditional RSI.
// @author       Alex Orekhov (script), Sylvain Vervoort (original idea)
// @param src    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length (int) Period of loopback
// @returns      (float) Series of asymmetrical RSI
export arsi(float src, simple int length) =>

    roc = ta.roc(src, 1)

    upCount = math.sum(roc >= 0 ? 1 : 0, length)
    upAlpha = 1 / upCount

    upSum = 0.0
    upSum := upAlpha * (roc >= 0 ? roc : 0) + (1 - upAlpha) * nz(upSum[1], upSum)

    downCount = length - upCount
    downAlpha = 1 / downCount

    downSum = 0.0
    downSum := downAlpha * (roc >= 0 ? 0 : math.abs(roc)) + (1 - downAlpha) * nz(downSum[1], downSum)

    arsi = fixnan(100 * upSum / (upSum + downSum))

// @function    ROC (Rate of Change). Measures the percentage change in price of an asset over a specified time period.
// @param source    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length    (int) Period of loopback
// @returns         (float) Series of ROC
export roc(float source, simple int length) =>
    100 * (source - source[length])/source[length]

// @function  Stochastic Oscillator. Compares the current price of an asset to its price range over a specified time period.
// @param kLengt        (int) Period of loopback to calculate the stochastic
// @param kSmoothing    (int) Period for smoothig stochastic
// @param dSmoothing    (int) Period for signal (moving average of stochastic)
// @param maTypeK       (int) Type of Moving Average for Stochastic Oscillator
// @param maTypeD       (int) Type of Moving Average for Stochastic Oscillator Signal
// @param almaOffsetKD  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average for Oscillator and Signal
// @param almaSigmaKD   (float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average for Oscillator and Signal
// @param lsmaOffSetKD  (int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average for Oscillator and Signal
// @returns             [float, float] A tuple of Stochastic Oscillator and Moving Average of Stochastic Oscillator
export stoch(simple int kLength, simple int kSmoothing, simple int dSmoothing,
  simple int maTypeK, simple int maTypeD,
  simple float almaOffsetKD=0.85, simple float almaSigmaKD=6, simple int lsmaOffSetKD=0) =>

	_k = ta.stoch(close, high, low, kLength)

	k = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeK, src=_k, len=kSmoothing, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetKD, inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaKD, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetKD)
	d = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeD, src=k, len=dSmoothing, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetKD, inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaKD, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetKD)

	[k, d]

// @function    Stochastic Oscillator. Customized source. Compares the current price of an asset to its price range over a specified time period.
// @param source        (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param kLength       (int) Period of loopback to calculate the stochastic
// @param kSmoothing    (int) Period for smoothig stochastic
// @param dSmoothing    (int) Period for signal (moving average of stochastic)
// @param maTypeK       (int) Type of Moving Average for Stochastic Oscillator
// @param maTypeD       (int) Type of Moving Average for Stochastic Oscillator Signal
// @param almaOffsetKD 	(float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average for Stoch and Signal
// @param almaSigmaKD 	(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average for Stoch and Signal
// @param lsmaOffSetKD 	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average for Stoch and Signal
// @returns             [float, float] A tuple of Stochastic Oscillator and Moving Average of Stochastic Oscillator
export stoch(float source, simple int kLength, simple int kSmoothing, simple int dSmoothing,
  simple int maTypeK, simple int maTypeD,
  simple float almaOffsetKD=0.85, simple float almaSigmaKD=6, simple int lsmaOffSetKD=0) =>

	_k = ta.stoch(source, ta.highest(source, 1), ta.lowest(source, 1), kLength)

	k = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeK, src=_k, len=kSmoothing, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetKD, inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaKD, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetKD)
	d = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeD, src=k, len=dSmoothing, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetKD, inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaKD, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetKD)

	[k, d]

// @function  TSI (True Strengh Index). Measures the price change, calculating the ratio of the price change (positive or negative) in relation to the absolute price change.
//    The values of both are smoothed twice to reduce noise, and the final result is normalized in a range between 100 and -100.
// @param source 	    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param firstSmoothLength	(int) First Smooth length
// @param secondSmoothLength	(int) Second Smooth length
// @param maType	    (int) Type of Moving Average for TSI
// @param almaOffset    (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigma	    (float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSet    (int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns             (float) TSI
export tsi(float source, simple int firstSmoothLength, simple int secondSmoothLength,
  simple int maType, simple float almaOffset=0.85, simple float almaSigma=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSet=0) =>

	priceChange = ta.change(source)
	double_smoothed_pc = double_smooth(priceChange, firstSmoothLength, secondSmoothLength, maType, almaOffset, almaSigma, lsmaOffSet)
	double_smoothed_abs_pc = double_smooth(math.abs(priceChange), firstSmoothLength, secondSmoothLength, maType, almaOffset, almaSigma, lsmaOffSet)
	100 * (double_smoothed_pc / double_smoothed_abs_pc)

// @function  SMIE (Stochastic Momentum Index Ergodic). 
//    The Stochastic Momentum Index (SMI) Ergodic indicator works much like the True Strength Index, 
//    except it uses a signal line in its market analysis.
//    This version also returns the histogram of the difference between the SMI and the signal, which is 
//    "SMIO - Stochastic Momentum Index Ergodic Oscillator".
// @param source            (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param lengthK           (int) Length for K%. Lengh for calculate SMI's oscillator.
// @param lengthD	        (int) Length for D%. lengh for smoothing SMI's oscillator.
// @param maTypeSMI         (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param almaOffsetSMI		  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSMI		  (float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSMI		  (int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @param maTypeSignal      (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param smoothingLengthSignal (int) Length for smoothing SMI's signal
// @param almaOffsetSignal  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSignal		(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSignal	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns               [float, float, float] A tuple with SMI, signal of SMI and histogram of difference
export smie(float source, simple int lengthK, simple int lengthD,
  simple int maTypeSMI,
  simple float almaOffsetSMI=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSMI=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSMI=0,

  simple int maTypeSignal, simple int smoothingLengthSignal,
  simple float almaOffsetSignal=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSignal=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSignal=0) =>

    tsi = tsi(source, lengthK, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)
    signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeSignal, src=tsi, len=smoothingLengthSignal, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetSignal,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaSignal, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetSignal)

    histogram = tsi - signal

    [tsi, signal, histogram]

// @function  SMI (Stochastic Momentum Index).
// @param lengthK           (int) Length for K%. Lengh for calculate SMI's oscillator.
// @param lengthD	        (int) Length for D%. lengh for smoothing SMI's oscillator.
// @param maTypeSMI         (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param almaOffsetSMI		(float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSMI		(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSMI		(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @param maTypeSignal      (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param smoothingLengthSignal (int) Length for smoothing SMI's signal
// @param almaOffsetSignal  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSignal	(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSignal	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns               [float, float, float] A tuple with SMI, signal of SMI and histogram of difference
export smi(simple int lengthK, simple int lengthD,
  simple int maTypeSMI,
  simple float almaOffsetSMI=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSMI=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSMI=0,

  simple int maTypeSignal, simple int smoothingLengthSignal,
  simple float almaOffsetSignal=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSignal=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSignal=0) =>

	highestHigh = ta.highest(lengthK)
    lowestLow = ta.lowest(lengthK)

    relativeRange = close - (highestHigh + lowestLow) / 2
    highestLowestRange = highestHigh - lowestLow

    relativeRangeSmooth = double_smooth(relativeRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)
    highestLowestRangeSmooth = double_smooth(highestLowestRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)

    smi = 200 * relativeRangeSmooth / highestLowestRangeSmooth

	signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeSignal, src=smi, len=smoothingLengthSignal, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetSignal,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaSignal, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetSignal)


	histogram = smi - signal

	[smi, signal, histogram]

// @function  SMI (Stochastic Momentum Index). Version with custom source.
// @param source            (float) Source to get the highest, lowest and relative range.
// @param lengthK           (int) Length K
// @param lengthD	        (int) Length D
// @param maTypeSMI         (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param almaOffsetSMI		(float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSMI		(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSMI		(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @param maTypeSignal      (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param smoothingLengthSignal (int) Length for smoothing SMI's signal
// @param almaOffsetSignal  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSignal	(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSignal	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns               [float, float, float] A tuple with SMI, signal of SMI and histogram of difference
export smi(float source, simple int lengthK, simple int lengthD,
  simple int maTypeSMI,
  simple float almaOffsetSMI=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSMI=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSMI=0,

  simple int maTypeSignal, simple int smoothingLengthSignal,
  simple float almaOffsetSignal=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSignal=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSignal=0) =>

	highestHigh = ta.highest(source, lengthK)
    lowestLow = ta.lowest(source, lengthK)

    relativeRange = source - (highestHigh + lowestLow) / 2
    highestLowestRange = highestHigh - lowestLow

    relativeRangeSmooth = double_smooth(relativeRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)
    highestLowestRangeSmooth = double_smooth(highestLowestRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)

    smi = 200 * relativeRangeSmooth / highestLowestRangeSmooth

	signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeSignal, src=smi, len=smoothingLengthSignal, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetSignal,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaSignal, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetSignal)

	histogram = smi - signal

	[smi, signal, histogram]

// @function  SMI (Stochastic Momentum Index). Version with custom source.
// @param sourceHigh        (float) Source for high
// @param sourceLow         (float) Source for low
// @param sourceRelativeRange    (float) Source for relative range
// @param lengthK           (int) Length K
// @param lengthD	        (int) Length D
// @param maTypeSMI         (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param almaOffsetSMI		(float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSMI		(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSMI		(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @param maTypeSignal      (int) Type of Moving Average for SMI
// @param smoothingLengthSignal (int) Length for smoothing SMI's signal
// @param almaOffsetSignal  (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigmaSignal	(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSetSignal	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns               [float, float, float] A tuple with SMI, signal of SMI and histogram of difference
export smi(float sourceHigh, float sourceLow, float sourceRelativeRange,
  simple int lengthK, simple int lengthD,
  simple int maTypeSMI,
  simple float almaOffsetSMI=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSMI=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSMI=0,

  simple int maTypeSignal, simple int smoothingLengthSignal,
  simple float almaOffsetSignal=0.85, simple float almaSigmaSignal=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSetSignal=0) =>

	highestHigh = ta.highest(sourceHigh, lengthK)
    lowestLow = ta.lowest(sourceLow, lengthK)

    relativeRange = sourceRelativeRange - (highestHigh + lowestLow) / 2
    highestLowestRange = highestHigh - lowestLow

    relativeRangeSmooth = double_smooth(relativeRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)
    highestLowestRangeSmooth = double_smooth(highestLowestRange, lengthD, lengthD, maTypeSMI, almaOffsetSMI, almaSigmaSMI, lsmaOffSetSMI)

    smi = 200 * relativeRangeSmooth / highestLowestRangeSmooth

	signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeSignal, src=smi, len=smoothingLengthSignal, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffsetSignal,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigmaSignal, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSetSignal)

	histogram = smi - signal

	[smi, signal, histogram]

// @function  Williams R% (Williams Percent Range). Compares the current price of an asset to its highest high and lowest low over a specified time period.
// @param source    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length    (int) Period of loopback
// @returns         (float) Series of Williams R%
export wpr(float source, simple int length) =>
    max = ta.highest(source, length)
	min = ta.lowest(source, length)
	100 * (source - max) / (max - min)

// @function  CCI (Commodity Channel Index). Measures the relationship between an asset's current price
//  and its moving average.
// Fun Facts:
// Is mean deviation the same as standard deviation?
// No, Mean Deviation (MD) and Standard Deviation (SD) are two different measures of dispersion, although both are used to quantify the variability of a data set in relation to its mean. Here are the main differences:
// Calculation:
// Mean Deviation is calculated by adding the absolute deviations of each value in relation to the mean and dividing by the number of observations.
// Standard Deviation is calculated by taking the square root of the mean of the squares of the deviations of each value in relation to the mean.
// Sensitivity to Outliers:
// Mean Deviation is less sensitive to outliers (extreme values) because it considers absolute deviations.
// Standard Deviation is more sensitive to outliers because it squares the deviations, giving greater weight to extreme values.
// // Unit of Measurement:

// Mean Deviation is expressed in the same unit of measurement as the original data.
// Standard Deviation is expressed in the unit of measurement of the original data squared
// (although the square root is used at the end, bringing it back to the original unit).

// Use in Statistics:

// Mean Deviation is less commonly used in statistics due to its lower mathematical efficiency compared
// to Standard Deviation.
// Standard Deviation is widely used in statistics and is the most frequently employed measure of dispersion
// due to its mathematical properties.

// Use in CCI:

// The CCI (Commodity Channel Index) indicator uses Mean Deviation in its calculation to measure price volatility.
// Standard Deviation is not used directly in the calculation of CCI, but is the basis for other indicators,
// such as Bollinger Bands. // In summary, although Mean Deviation and Standard Deviation are both measures of dispersion,
// they differ in their calculation, sensitivity to outliers, unit of measurement, and use in statistics and technical analysis.
// The CCI chooses to use Mean Deviation in its formula due to its lower sensitivity to extreme values ​​in prices.

// @param source        (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param lengthMA      (int) Period of loopback (length of moving average)
// @param maType        (int) Type of Moving Average
// @param almaOffset    (float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigma     (float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSet    (int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @param lenghDEV      (int) Length for mean deviation
// @param maType        (int) Type of Moving Average used in Mean Deviation
// @returns             (float) Series of CCI
export cci(float source, simple int lengthMA, simple int maType,
  simple float almaOffset=0.85, simple float almaSigma=6, simple int lsmaOffSet=0,
  simple int lenghDEV, simple int maTypeDEV) =>

	ma = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maType, src=source, len=lengthMA, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffset,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigma, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSet)

	(source - ma) / (0.015 * dev(source, lenghDEV, maTypeDEV, almaOffset, almaSigma, lsmaOffSet))

// @function  UO (Ultimate Oscilator). Combines three different time periods to help identify possible reversal points.
// @param fastLength    (int) Fast period of loopback
// @param middleLength  (int) Middle period of loopback
// @param slowLength    (int) Slow period of loopback
// @returns             (float) Series of Ultimate Oscilator
export ultimateOscillator(simple int fastLength, simple int middleLength, simple int slowLength) =>
    high_ = math.max(high, close[1])
    low_ = math.min(low, close[1])

    bp = close - low_
    tr_ = high_ - low_

    avg7 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, fastLength)
    avg14 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, middleLength)
    avg28 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, slowLength)

    100 * (4*avg7 + 2*avg14 + avg28)/7

// @function 	UO (Ultimate Oscilator). Customized source. Combines three different time periods to help identify possible reversal points.
// @param source        (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param fastLength    (int) Fast period of loopback
// @param middleLength  (int) Middle period of loopback
// @param slowLength    (int) Slow period of loopback
// @returns             (float) Series of Ultimate Oscilator
export ultimateOscillator(float source, simple int fastLength, simple int middleLength, simple int slowLength) =>
    high_ = math.max(ta.highest(source, 1), source[1])
    low_ = math.min(ta.lowest(source, 1), source[1])

    bp = source - low_
    tr_ = high_ - low_

    avg7 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, fastLength)
    avg14 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, middleLength)
    avg28 = weightedAverage(bp, tr_, slowLength)

    100 * (4*avg7 + 2*avg14 + avg28)/7

// @function 	MACD (Moving Average Convergence/Divergence). Shows the difference between short-term and long-term exponential moving averages.
// @param source            (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param fastLength 	  	(int) Period for fast moving average
// @param slowLength 	  	(int) Period for slow moving average
// @param signalLength		(int) Signal length
// @param maTypeFast 	  	(int) Type of fast moving average
// @param maTypeSlow 	  	(int) Type of slow moving average
// @param maTypeMACD 	  	(int) Type of MACD moving average
// @param almaOffset 	  	(float) Offset for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param almaSigma 	  	(float) Sigma for Arnaud Legoux Moving Average
// @param lsmaOffSet 	  	(int) Offset for Least Squares Moving Average
// @returns                 [float, float, float] A tuple with MACD, Signal, and Histgram
export macd(float source, simple int fastLength, simple int slowLength, simple int signalLength,
  simple int maTypeFast, simple int maTypeSlow, simple int maTypeMACD,
  simple float almaOffset=0.85, simple float almaSigma=6,
  simple int lsmaOffSet=0) =>

    fastMA = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeFast, src=source, len=fastLength, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffset,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigma, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSet)

    slowMA = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeSlow, src=source, len=slowLength, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffset,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigma, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSet)

    macd = fastMA - slowMA

    signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=maTypeMACD, src=macd, len=signalLength, inputAlmaOffset=almaOffset,
      inputAlmaSigma=almaSigma, lsmaOffset=lsmaOffSet)


    histogram = macd - signal

    [macd, signal, histogram]

// @function  Fisher Transform. Normalize prices into a Gaussian normal distribution.
// @param length 	    (int) Period for loopback
// @returns             [float, float] A tuple with Fisher Transform and signal
export fisher(simple int length) =>

    high_ = ta.highest(hl2, length)
    low_ = ta.lowest(hl2, length)

    value = 0.0
    value := UTIL.round(.66 * ((hl2 - low_) / (high_ - low_) - .5) + .67 * nz(value[1]))

    fish1 = 0.0
    fish1 := .5 * math.log((1 + value) / (1 - value)) + .5 * nz(fish1[1])
    fish2 = fish1[1]
    [fish1, fish2]

// @function  Fisher Transform. Customized source. Normalize prices into a Gaussian normal distribution.
// @param sourceHigh 	 (float) Source of series for high values
// @param sourceLow 	 (float) Source of series for low values
// @param length 	  	(int) Period for loopback
// @returns             [float, float] A tuple with Fisher Transform and signal
export fisher(float sourceHigh, float sourceLow, simple int length) =>

    high_ = ta.highest(sourceHigh, length)
    low_ = ta.lowest(sourceLow, length)
    hl2_ = (sourceHigh + sourceLow)/2

    value = 0.0
    value := UTIL.round(.66 * ((hl2_ - low_) / (high_ - low_) - .5) + .67 * nz(value[1]))

    fish1 = 0.0
    fish1 := .5 * math.log((1 + value) / (1 - value)) + .5 * nz(fish1[1])
    fish2 = fish1[1]

    [fish1, fish2]

// @function  Inverse Fisher Transform.
//    Transform the values of the Fisher Transform into a smaller and more easily interpretable scale is
//	  through the application of an inverse transformation to the hyperbolic tangent function.
//	  This transformation takes the values of the FT, which range from -infinity to +infinity,
//    to a scale limited between -1 and +1, allowing them to be more easily visualized and compared.
// @param source 	    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length 	    (int) Period for loopback
// @param subtrahend    (int) Subtrahend. Useful in bounded indicators. For example, in RSI use a value of -50.
// @param subtrahend    (int) Denominator. Useful in unbounded indicators. For example, in CCI.
// @returns             (float) Series of Inverse Fisher Transform
export inverseFisher(float source, simple int length, simple float subtrahend=0, simple int denominator=1) =>

    v1 = 0.1 * (source - subtrahend)/denominator
    v2 = ta.wma(v1, length)

    ift = (math.exp(2 * v2) - 1) / (math.exp(2 * v2) + 1)

// @function  Premier Stochastic Oscillator (PSO).
//    Normalizes the standard stochastic oscillator by applying a five-period double exponential smoothing
//    average of the %K value, resulting in a symmetric scale of 1 to -1.
// @param length 	    (int) Period for loopback
// @param smoothlen     (int) Period for smoothing
// @returns 		    (float) Series of PSO
export premierStoch(simple int length, simple int smoothlen) =>

    sk = ta.stoch( close, high, low, length)
    len = math.round(math.sqrt( smoothlen ))

    nsk = 0.1 * ( sk - 50 )
    ss = ta.ema( ta.ema( nsk, len ), len )
    expss = math.exp( ss )
    pso = ( expss - 1 )/( expss + 1 )

// @function  Premier Stochastic Oscillator (PSO) of custom source.
//    Normalizes the source by applying a five-period double exponential smoothing average.
// @param source        (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param smoothlen     (int) Period for smoothing
// @param subtrahend    (int) Subtrahend. Useful in bounded indicators. For example, in RSI use a value of -50.
// @param denominator    (int) Denominator. Useful in unbounded indicators. For example, in CCI.
// @returns             (float) Series of PSO
export premierStoch(float source, simple int smoothlen, simple float subtrahend=0, simple int denominator=1) =>

	len = math.round(math.sqrt( smoothlen ))

	nsk = 0.1 * ( source - subtrahend )/denominator
	ss = ta.ema( ta.ema( nsk, len ), len )
	expss = math.exp( ss )
	pso = ( expss - 1 )/( expss + 1 )

// @function  Momentum. Measures the change in price over a specified period of time.
// @param source 	    (float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param length 	    (int) Period for loopback
// @returns           (float) Series of Momentum
export momentum(float source, simple int length) =>
    mom = source - source[length]

// @function Know Sure Thing in Trend Indicators. 
//    The Know Sure Thing (KST) indicator is a momentum oscillator that compares the rate of change of four different price cycles.
//    The KST indicator is used to identify major stock market trends and generate buy and sell signals.
// @param lengthRoc1 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 1
// @param lengthRoc2 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 2
// @param lengthRoc3 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 3
// @param lengthRoc4 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 4
// @param lengthMA1 	(int) Period for Moving Average 1
// @param typeMA1 	(int) Type of Moving Average 1
// @param lengthMA2 	(int) Period for Moving Average 2
// @param typeMA2 	(int) Type of Moving Average 2
// @param lengthMA3 	(int) Period for Moving Average 3
// @param typeMA3 	(int) Type of Moving Average 3
// @param lengthMA4 	(int) Period for Moving Average 4
// @param typeMA4 	(int) Type of Moving Average 4
// @param lengthSignal 	(int) Period for Signal
// @param typeSignal 	(int) Type of Signal
// @returns 		[float, float] A tuple with KST and Signal
export kst(simple int lengthRoc1, simple int lengthRoc2, simple int lengthRoc3, simple int lengthRoc4,
  simple int lengthMA1, simple int typeMA1, simple int lengthMA2, simple int typeMA2,
  simple int lengthMA3, simple int typeMA3, simple int lengthMA4, simple int typeMA4,
  simple int lengthSignal, simple int typeSignal) =>

    roc1 = ta.roc(close, lengthRoc1)
    roc2 = ta.roc(close, lengthRoc2)
    roc3 = ta.roc(close, lengthRoc3)
    roc4 = ta.roc(close, lengthRoc4)

    ma1 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA1, src=roc1, len=lengthMA1)
    ma2 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA2, src=roc2, len=lengthMA2)
    ma3 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA3, src=roc3, len=lengthMA3)
    ma4 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA4, src=roc4, len=lengthMA4)

    kst = ma1 + (2 * ma2) + (3 * ma3) + (4 * ma4)
    signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeSignal, src=kst, len=lengthSignal)

    [kst, signal]

// @function Know Sure Thing in Trend Indicators. Customized source.
//    The Know Sure Thing (KST) indicator is a momentum oscillator that compares the rate of change of four different price cycles
//    The KST indicator is used to identify major stock market trends and generate buy and sell signals.
// @param source 		(float) Source of series (close, high, low, etc.)
// @param lengthRoc1 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 1
// @param lengthRoc2 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 2
// @param lengthRoc3 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 3
// @param lengthRoc4 		(int) Period for Rate of Change 4
// @param lengthMA1 	(int) Period for Moving Average 1
// @param typeMA1 	(int) Type of Moving Average 1
// @param lengthMA2 	(int) Period for Moving Average 2
// @param typeMA2 	(int) Type of Moving Average 2
// @param lengthMA3 	(int) Period for Moving Average 3
// @param typeMA3 	(int) Type of Moving Average 3
// @param lengthMA4 	(int) Period for Moving Average 4
// @param typeMA4 	(int) Type of Moving Average 4
// @param lengthSignal 	(int) Period for Signal
// @param typeSignal 	(int) Type of Signal
// @returns 		[float, float] A tuple with KST and Signal
export kst(float source, simple int lengthRoc1, simple int lengthRoc2, simple int lengthRoc3, simple int lengthRoc4,
  simple int lengthMA1, simple int typeMA1, simple int lengthMA2, simple int typeMA2,
  simple int lengthMA3, simple int typeMA3, simple int lengthMA4, simple int typeMA4,
  simple int lengthSignal, simple int typeSignal) =>

    roc1 = ta.roc(source, lengthRoc1)
    roc2 = ta.roc(source, lengthRoc2)
    roc3 = ta.roc(source, lengthRoc3)
    roc4 = ta.roc(source, lengthRoc4)

    ma1 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA1, src=roc1, len=lengthMA1)
    ma2 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA2, src=roc2, len=lengthMA2)
    ma3 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA3, src=roc3, len=lengthMA3)
    ma4 = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeMA4, src=roc4, len=lengthMA4)

    kst = ma1 + (2 * ma2) + (3 * ma3) + (4 * ma4)
    signal = MAP.getMovingAverage(typeID=typeSignal, src=kst, len=lengthSignal)

    [kst, signal]

// #endregion }
